    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-04-07T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-04-07T15:00:00-05:00" n="548"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d548">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.226/3: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France (<persName type="from"
                            >Leahy</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-04-07T22:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 7, 1942—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 8—9:29 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>515. The Department’s decision to establish a Consulate General at Brazzaville
                    has caused little comment in Vichy and the press of unoccupied France (we hear
                    on orders of the Ministry of Information) has published nothing on this subject.
                    Officials with whom we have spoken seem to take a practical view of this
                    decision and seem to recognize our vital interest in seeing to it that the flow
                    of American supplies to the Near East via Africa is not impeded.</p>
                <p>Today’s Paris press, however, develops the theme that this constitutes
                    practically official recognition of the government of de Gaulle<note n="91"
                        xml:id="d548fn91">Gen. Charles de Gaulle, President of the National
                        Committee of the Free French at London.</note> and is but another form of
                    American blackmail in an attempt to keep France from playing her “proper role in
                    the constitution of a new Europe”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Leahy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
